	title = {Origin of Spin-Dependent Tunneling Through Chiral Molecules},
	volume = {123},
	issn = {1932-7447, 1932-7455},
	url = {https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.jpcc.9b05020},
	doi = {10.1021/acs.jpcc.9b05020},
	abstract = {\#\#\# Summary:

Simple and intuitive effective-continuum (quasi-1D) model in the single-electron picture on the mechanism of {CISS} (confined to helical motion within a dipole field). The authors argue that the helical molecule structure is the core factor behind transport in {CISS}: the {SOI} behaves as an effective Zeeman splitting-field, its vector direction varying with helical coordinates. After a gauge transformation, the Zeeman field is made a constant and a quasi-Rashba {SOI} emerges in the Hamiltonian. Note that {TRS} is also preserved in the model. (Bardarson's condition does not apply since the model is by definition not single-channel.)

Solving for the energy spectrum, an avoided-crossing occurs when the radius of the helix is non-zero. Within the band gap, spin and momentum directions are locked together, giving rise to spin polarisation (near unidirectional spin currents). Numerical calculations of polarisation and transmission follow, exhibiting critical length.

The authors identify that the model only explains {CISS} in a narrow energy range, leaving out room-temperature observations. To circumvent this, they account for a large dipole potential (experimentally found; no cites given in paper; {KIV}), **extending the {CISS} range from the avoided-crossing band gap to the whole dipole potential range**.

The large dipole field localises low-energy electrons at the molecule edges, with gradual wavefunction decay down the molecule. Total transmission decreases as a result, but transmission is comparatively enhanced when radius (or curvature) and level-index are non-zero. However, spin polarisation is enhanced. These properties are in line with experimental 


\#\#\# Comments:
- Variant of Utsumi et al. (2021): different model. Utsumi et al. gives a phenomological account, while this is more mechanistic.


